english:
  title: A Preface for Park Jungseo's Return to Pay Respects to His Mother
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Friendships formed by circumstance and mutual advantage are mere surface acquaintance. But friendships grounded in virtue—these are true friendships. Only then does knowing one another reach its fullest meaning. Do I know Park Jungseo in this profound way, or do I perhaps fall short? When Park Jungseo was dismissed from court and prepared to return home to pay respects to his mother, he asked me to write this account of his departure. I shall not cite other examples, but rather let my knowledge of the man himself bear witness.

    Since his youth, Park Jungseo served at court, holding positions of honor and proximity to the throne. People celebrated his prominence, yet he never gloried in it. At home, morning and evening he attended his parents with filial devotion. His fraternal love and respect were beautiful to behold. And yet he seemed always possessed of a certain discontent. For at court, he thought only of fulfilling his duties perfectly—whatever needed doing, he did without hesitation, arriving at dawn and staying through the evening, tireless and ever more devoted. But what does promotion or dismissal have to do with me? How could such things bring me honor or shame? This was Park's heart. At home, he served his father with reverence and his mother with deep affection. Yet knowing his mother dwelt distant in the countryside, he longed for the day when both parents might dwell under one roof, and brothers might play together as children beneath it. This too was Park's heart.

    Thus when dismissal came, he remained serene, as though nothing had changed. No resentment crossed his face. He spoke to his friends, consulted his father and elder brother, and decided on only one course: to return and pay respects to his mother. This is how I know Park's journey is no mere flight of a small man from hardship—it is the long-cherished yearning of a devoted son, now granted its opportunity.

    Consider this: serving one's parents and serving one's sovereign follow the same way. When a son fulfills his duty to his parents, and a minister fulfills his duty to his sovereign, both establish the names of filial piety and loyalty. The sage Cheng Zi understood loyalty as the completion of one's duties; only then did people realize that filial piety too is loyalty, and nothing more. Thus, when a minister completes his duties at court, this is filial piety in service; when a son completes his duties at home, this is loyalty in service. One who rejoices when appointed and resents dismissal cannot truly complete his duty to his sovereign. One who grows familiar when near and forgetful when distant cannot truly complete his duty to his parents. Filial piety does not vary with distance or proximity; loyalty does not change with service or retirement. Only those who complete their duties can achieve this.

    Do I truly know Park Jungseo deeply, or do I fall short? Let Park answer me by knowing me in return as I know him. Should Park not abandon me in days to come, then I will have no doubt that we truly know one another. Let this serve as my preface.
  footnotes:
    - 'Park Jungseo (朴中書): ''Jungseo'' (中書) is a title referring to his position as a secretary or central official, not his personal name. He held an important position in the Goryeo court.'
    - The Neo-Confucian philosophy referenced here, particularly regarding the unity of loyalty (忠) and filial piety (孝), reflects the ethical framework of the Goryeo literati of the 14th century.
    - The 'Cheng Zi' (程子) mentioned is Cheng Yi, a foundational Neo-Confucian philosopher whose interpretation of loyalty as 'completing one's duties' was highly influential in East Asian thought.
